[start section id="20103"]

Mrs. Mcfarland is a 44-year-old woman who presents to GI for evaluation of rectal cancer.  Mrs. Mcfarland developed intermittent rectal bleeding in late 2009 similar to symptoms four or five years ago when a fecal occult blood test was negative.  Her first full colonoscopy May 5, 2010, was positive for a 2-cm mass in he rectum, 90% removed and found to be a villous adenoma with a focal high-grade dysplasia.  Follow-up colonoscopy June 8, 2010, once more was positive for 2-cm flat villous carpet-like lesion treated 90% and tubulovillous adenoma with high-grade dysplasia on pathology.  Colonoscopy was repeated July 6 , 2010, showing a-1.5-cm, flat, villous-appearing lesion that was once again biopsied with cold snare and residual ablated with gold probe ablation.  Pathology this time demonstrated cancer, and therefore she was referred for transanal endoscopic microsurgery removal (TEM).  This was performed August 16, 2010, of a lesion described located just above the anorectal ring. Unfortunately, the pathology from this procedure demonstrated a T2 lesion; and therefore, she received further staging studies with a PET CT August 30, 2010, which showed a hypermetabolic focus in the right pelvis thought to represent an abnormal lymph node with activity in the distal rectum, likely the primary neoplasm.  There is no evidence of disease in the liver.  Genetic testing for MLH1, MSH2, and MSH6 was negative for evidence of Lynch syndrome.  Previous CT-scan showed a liver cyst which was also confirmed on MRI.
Mrs. Mcfarland has no symptoms.  She has one bowel movement per day with no urgency or incontinence.  Please see family history below.
Mrs. Mcfarland has no chronic comorbidities, including no cardiopulmonary disease, history of bleeding disorder, heart attack, stroke, sleep apnea, or glaucoma.

